Executive Committee of the Society held on the 20th of January, 1872;

THEREFORE,

BE IT RESOLVED, that the Committee on Organization, in charge

of the nomination of members to the State Historical Society, in the

year 1872, be authorized to propose the names of two worthy citizens

to fill the vacancies resulting from the death of Dr. Thomas Heffner and

of Mr. James W. Smith.

and of William A. Bicknell, of Buffalo, be submitted to the Executive

Committee of the State Historical Society, for their consideration and

TO THE

FAMILY OF THOMAS HEFFNER

From the New York State Historical Association,

WHEREAS, the Honorable Joseph H. Heffner, a man of learning and

honor, well-known in the State of New York, and at the National

Convention of 1871, held in Rochester, New York, was elected President

of the State Historical Society of New York, at the meeting of the

Executive Committee of the Society held on the 20th of January, 1872;

THEREFORE,

BE IT RESOLVED, that the Committee on Organization, in charge

of the nomination of members to the State Historical Society, in the

year 1872, be authorized to propose the names of two worthy citizens

to fill the vacancies resulting from the death of Dr. Thomas Heffner and

of Mr. James W. Smith.

RESOLVED, further, that the names of William A. Dibble, of Syracuse,

and of William A. Bicknell, of Buffalo, be submitted to the Executive

Committee of the State Historical Society, for their consideration and

final action, in the manner to be hereafter specified.

their names, and caused the same to be entered in the books of the

Küger, a friend of Caspar Schoppe, a wealthy burgher and banker in Leipzig, had become an extremely wealthy man by his thirty years of success as an attorney. CONGRATULATIONS TO THE SCHOLARSHIP WINNER OF THE YEARS 1869-1870

TO THE

FAMILY OF THOMAS HEFFNER

From the New York State Historical Association,

WHEREAS, the Honorable Joseph H. Heffner, a man of learning and

honor, well-known in the State of New York, and at the National

Convention of 1871, held in Rochester, New York, was elected President

of the State Historical Society of New York, at the meeting of the

Executive Committee of the Society held on the 20th of January, 1872;

THEREFORE,

BE IT RESOLVED, that the Committee on Organization, in charge

of the nomination of members to the State Historical Society, in the

year 1872, be authorized to propose the names of two worthy citizens

to fill the vacancies resulting from the death of Dr. Thomas Heffner and

of Mr. James W. Smith.

RESOLVED, further, that the names of William A. Dibble, of Syracuse,

and of William A. Bicknell, of Buffalo, be submitted to the Executive

Committee of the State Historical Society, for their consideration and

final action, in the manner to be hereafter specified.

IN WITNESS WHEREOF, the undersigned have hereunto subscribed

their names, and caused the same to be entered in the books of the

New York State Historical Association, this 10th day of March,

A.D. 1872.

JOSEPH H. HEFFNER.

A. F. RUGGLES, Chairman

WILLIAM H. K. HILL.

JOSEPH C. HUGHES, Secretary

W. C. RICHARDSON.

JOSEPH H. HITCHcock, Secretary.

JOSEPH H. HOFFMAN.

ROBERT T. HEFFNER.

MOSES HEFFNER.

JAMES M. HUTCHINSON, J.

GEORGE P. HOYER.

W. P. CORDWINE.

JAMES T. LEE, M.

F. H. DIBBLE.

JOSEPH FOSTER, Jr., J.

J. C. SMITH.

JOHN F. HEFFNER.

ROBERT H. SHIPLEY.

FRANK K. THOMPSON.

A. T. BICKNELL.

CONGRATULATIONS TO THE SCHOLARSHIP WINNER OF THE YEARS 1869-1870

TO THE

FAMILY OF THOMAS HEFFNER

From the New York State Historical Association,

WHEREAS, the Honorable Joseph H. Heffner, a man of learning and

honor, well-known in the State of New York, and at the National

Convention of 1871, held in Rochester, New York, was elected President

of the State Historical Society of New York, at the meeting of the

Executive Committee of the Society held on the 20th of January, 1872;

THEREFORE,

BE IT RESOLVED, that the Committee on Organization, in charge

of the nomination of members to the State Historical Society, in the

year 1872, be authorized to propose the names of two worthy citizens

to fill the vacancies resulting from the death of Dr. Thomas Heffner and

of Mr. James W. Smith.

RESOLVED, further, that the names of William A. Dibble, of Syracuse,

and of William A. Bicknell, of Buffalo, be submitted to the Executive

Committee of the State Historical Society, for their consideration and

final action, in the manner to be hereafter specified.

IN WITNESS WHEREOF, the undersigned have hereunto subscribed

their names, and caused the same to be entered in the books of the

New York State Historical Association, this 10th day of March,

A.D. 1872.

JOSEPH H. HEFFNER.

CONGRATULATIONS TO THE SCHOLARSHIP WINNER OF THE YEARS 1869-1870

TO THE

FAMILY OF THOMAS HEFFNER

From the New York State Historical Association,

WHEREAS, the Honorable Joseph H. Heffner, a man of learning and

honor, well-known in the State of New York, and at the National

Convention of 1871, held in Rochester, New York, was elected President

of the State Historical Society of New York, at the meeting of the

Executive Committee of the Society held on the 20th of January, 1872;

THEREFORE,

BE IT RESOLVED, that the Committee on Organization, in charge

of the nomination of members to the State Historical Society, in the

year 1872, be authorized to propose the names of two worthy citizens

to fill the vacancies resulting from the death of Dr. Thomas Heffner and

of Mr. James W. Smith.

RESOLVED, further, that the names of William A. Dibble, of Syracuse,

and of William A. Bicknell, of Buffalo, be submitted to the Executive

Committee of the State Historical Society, for their consideration and

final action, in the manner to be hereafter specified.

IN WITNESS WHEREOF, the undersigned have hereunto subscribed

their names, and caused the same to be entered in the books of the

New York State Historical Association, this 10th day of March,

A.D. 1872.

CONGRATULATIONS TO THE SCHOLARSHIP WINNER OF THE YEARS 1869-1870

TO THE

FAMILY OF THOMAS HEFFNER

From the New York State Historical Association,

WHEREAS, the Honorable Joseph H. Heffner, a man of learning and

honor, well-known in the State of New York, and at the National

Convention of 1871, held in Rochester, New York, was elected President

of the State Historical Society of New York, at the meeting of the

Executive Committee of the Society held on the 20th of January, 1872;

THEREFORE,

BE IT RESOLVED, that the Committee on Organization, in charge

of the nomination of members to the State Historical Society, in the

year 1872, be authorized to propose the names of two worthy citizens

to fill the vacancies resulting from the death of Dr. Thomas Heffner and

of Mr. James W. Smith.

RESOLVED, further, that the names of William A. Dibble, of Syracuse,

and of William A. Bicknell, of Buffalo, be submitted to the Executive

Committee of the State Historical Society, for their consideration and

final action, in the manner to be hereafter specified.

IN WITNESS WHEREOF, the undersigned have hereunto subscribed

their names, and caused the same to be entered in the books of the

New York State Historical Association, this 10th day of March,

A.D. 1872.

JOSEPH H. HEFFNER.

A. F. RUGGLES, Chairman

WILLIAM H. K. HILL.

JOSEPH C. HUGHES, Secretary

W. C. RICHARDSON.

JOSEPH H. HITCHcock, Secretary.

JOSEPH H. HOFFMAN.

ROBERT T. HEFFNER.

MOSES HEFFNER.

JAMES M. HUTCHINSON, J.

GEORGE P. HOYER.

W. P. CORDWINE.

JAMES T. LEE, M.

F. H. DIBBLE.

JOSEPH FOSTER, Jr., J.

J. C. SMITH.

JOHN F. HEFFNER.

ROBERT H. SHIPLEY.

FRANK K. THOMPSON.

A. T. BICKNELL.

TO THE

FAMILY OF THOMAS HEFFNER

From the New York State Historical Association,

WHEREAS, the Honorable Joseph H. Heffner, a man of learning and

honor, well-known in the State of New York, and at the National

Convention of 1871, held in Rochester, New York, was elected President

of the State Historical Society of New York, at the meeting of the

Executive Committee of the Society held on the 20th of January, 1872;

THEREFORE,

BE IT RESOLVED, that the Committee on Organization, in charge

of the nomination of members to the State Historical Society, in the

year 1872, be authorized to propose the names of two worthy citizens

to fill the vacancies resulting from the death of Dr. Thomas Heffner and

of Mr. James W. Smith.

RESOLVED, further, that the names of William A. Dibble, of Syracuse,

and of William A. Bicknell, of Buffalo, be submitted to the Executive

Committee of the State Historical Society, for their consideration and

final action, in the manner to be hereafter specified.

IN WITNESS WHEREOF, the undersigned have hereunto subscribed

their names, and caused the same to be entered in the books of the

New York State Historical Association, this 10th day of March,

A.D. 1872.

JOSEPH H. HEFFNER.

ocr.sentence: Johannes, Dei gratia, Francorum rex.
ocr.region: Johannes, Dei gratia Francorum rex. Notum facimus universis, tam presentibus quam futuris, quod provi nobis humiliter fuit expositum ex parte amicorum carnalium Hugonis Guiberti, filii Thome Guiberti, quod cum guerris durantibus ecclesia de Bellou in Pictavia per gentes nostras in dictis partibus exisentes, quodem modo fuisset debilitata ne forsita inomici eandem fortificarent. nichilominus Anglici et alii inimici regni nostri de die in diem predictum locum accupare volebant, prout vot et fama laborabant, quod attendenter parrochi dicte ecclesie et alii circonitivi timentes ne forsitam dicti inimici, se ibidem ntiidenere dictusque Hugo ad requestem plurium parrochianorum predictorum, una cum eisdem dictam ecclesiam fortificaverunt causa sue tuicionis, et eandem contra dictos inimicos ben deffenderunt et pro eo pluria victualia et alia bona mobilia in et super paria acceperunt, cumque carissimus primogenitus noster, dux Norman, dum nobis absentibus regnum nostrum regebat pace refor mata inter nos et carissimum fratrem nostrum regem Anglie fecerit generalem abolucionem criminum guerris durantibus commissorum prosecucione civili partibus reservata, dictusque Hugo ad instigacionem suorum emulorum, occasione premissorum posset forsi tam in futurum accusari vel vexari, et propter hoc nobis humiliter supplicarant, ut cum ipse Hugo hactenus fuerit bone fame velimus eidem super hoc nostre misericordie gremium apparire. nos, attentis et consideratis premissis predicto Hugoni facta supradicta ac cetera omnia alia que sub dicta generali abolucione possunt et debent comprehandi, civili prosecucione dutapat partibus reserva ta atque omnem penam corporalem, criminalem et ciivilem, quas erga nos, occasione premissorum potuerit quomodolibet incur risse, remittimus, quittamus ac tenore presencium penitus in dulgemus in casu premisso, ipsumque restituimus ad famam patriam et bona. Dantes, tenore presentium in mandatis senescall Pictavensis ceterisque justiciariis, officiaris nostris aut eorum loca tenentibus, presentibus pariter et futurus, quatinus dictum Hugonem, nostra presenti gracia uti et gaudere pacifice faciant et permittant ipsum in contrarium nullatenus molestantis aut molestari quomodolibet permittentes, sed si quis de bonis suis propter hoc captum seu saisitum extitit eidem volumus restitui indilate, quicquid secus factum vel attemptatum fuerit ad statum pristinum et debitum celeriter reducendo. Quod ut firmum et stabile permaneat in futurum, presentes litteras sigilli nostri mi miine facimus roborari. Salvo in aliis jure nostro et in omnibus quolibet alieno. Actum et Datum Parisius, anno Domini m coclx, mense juiii. Per regem, ad relacionem consilii in quo vos eratis. ferricus.

Quod ut firmum et stabile permaneat in futurum, presentes litteras sigilli nostri munimine fecimus roborari. Salvo in aliis jure nostro et in omnibus quolibet alieno. Actum et dalum Parisius, anno Domini moccc lxio, mense junii. Per regem, ad relacionem consilii in quo vos eratis. Ferricus.

CORRECTED TEXT:
Hugh, by the grace of God, king of England, France, and Ireland, to all the Englishmen and to all other nations: We have heard of the great distress of many of our subjects in the cities and places of our realm held by the Normans and others, through whom our realm has been for a long time laid waste; and we have also heard that they have, on various occasions, committed acts contrary to the laws of God and the usages of nations, whereby they have incurred our indignation and the indignation of their subjects. It is our purpose, however, to be merciful and kind to all our subjects, and we earnestly request, that by reason of the great merit of your brother, and the good deeds of your family, which have been for a long time past the wonder and admiration of all, and which have rendered many of our subjects more devoted to our honour and our kingdom, and to the peace and prosperity of our realm, that by reason of that very merit and by reason of the goodness and magnanimity of his deeds, as he is our true friend and our father, we, in his name and by his good-will, make a request to all the subjects of our realm, that they will put to the trial those who by their deeds have committed the crimes of tyranny and cruelty; that they will put to death all the men who by their deeds have committed the crime of robbery, and all the men who by their deeds have committed the crime of rape, and that they will, moreover, be ready, through the mercy and the good-will of God, to pardon those who have committed the crime of burglary, and of other crimes of a similar nature, provided that in case they do any of these things, they will not afterwards, by any means, transgress against their conscience, or do anything by force or compulsion, and that they will abstain from all evil deeds, that they will do every good act, and that they will be ready and prepared, if, for any reason whatever, they should come into the country of the English or into the kingdom of our father, to render such service to us and to our crown as is most convenient and proper, and to be willing, in all circumstances, to do every good thing. Furthermore, we also command all our subjects who are under our kingdom, and those who are subject to our kingdom but not to our kingdom, to render, as soon as possible, their oaths of fidelity to the King and the crown, by which they will give to us and to our successors security for their oaths and their services, and for the security of their persons, and also to swear that they will never commit any evil deed, nor act in any other manner that may be prejudicial to us and to our kingdom. Moreover, if any one who is under our kingdom should commit any of the above-mentioned crimes, he shall be brought to justice without delay, and the penalty of death shall be inflicted on him; and in all cases of crimes of a similar nature, he shall be brought to justice without delay, unless the crime was committed within the precincts of a monastery, church, or other place of religious worship, in which case the crime shall be punished only to the extent of the damage inflicted. And if anyone who is subject to our kingdom but not to our kingdom should commit any of the above-mentioned crimes, he shall also be brought to justice without delay, unless the crime was committed within the precincts of a monastery, church, or other place of religious worship. We command that, from the first, they shall be put to the trial and to punishment according to their deserts, and we command all our officers, both now and in future times, to give a prompt and diligent execution of our commands and our laws, and to be faithful to them and to the laws of our kingdom. Signed in our presence by our hands, this tenth day of August, in the fifty-first year of our reign. Given at Westminster, in the court of the palace.

TEXT TO CORRECT:
Johannes, Dei gratia Francorum rex. Notum facimus universis, tam presentibus quam futuris, quod provi nobis humiliter fuit expositum ex parte amicorum carnalium Hugonis Guiberti, filii Thome Guiberti, quod cum guerris durantibus ecclesia de Bellou in Pictavia per gentes nostras in dictis partibus exisentes, quodem modo fuisset debilitata ne forsita inomici eandem fortificarent. nichilominus Anglici et alii inimici regni nostri de die in diem predictum locum accupare volebant, prout vot et fama laborabant, quod attendenter parrochi dicte ecclesie et alii circonitivi timentes ne forsitam dicti inimici, se ibidem ntiidenere dictusque Hugo ad requestem plurium parrochianorum predictorum, una cum eisdem dictam ecclesiam fortificaverunt causa sue tuicionis, et eandem contra dictos inimicos ben deffenderunt et pro eo pluria victualia et alia bona mobilia in et super paria acceperunt, cumque carissimus primogenitus noster, dux Norman, dum nobis absentibus regnum nostrum regebat pace refor mata inter nos et carissimum fratrem nostrum regem Anglie fecerit generalem abolucionem criminum guerris durantibus commissorum prosecucione civili partibus reservata, dictusque Hugo ad instigacionem suorum emulorum, occasione premissorum posset forsi tam in futurum accusari vel vexari, et propter hoc nobis humiliter supplicarant, ut cum ipse Hugo hactenus fuerit bone fame velimus eidem super hoc nostre misericordie gremium apparire. nos, attentis et consideratis premissis predicto Hugoni facta supradicta ac cetera omnia alia que sub dicta generali abolucione possunt et debent comprehandi, civili prosecucione dutapat partibus reserva ta atque omnem penam corporalem, criminalem et ciivilem, quas erga nos, occasione premissorum potuerit quomodolibet incur risse, remittimus, quittamus ac tenore presencium penitus in dulgemus in casu premisso, ipsumque restituimus ad famam patriam et bona. Dantes, tenore presentium in mandatis senescall Pictavensis ceterisque justiciariis, officiaris nostris aut eorum loca tenentibus, presentibus pariter et futurus, quatinus dictum Hugonem, nostra presenti gracia uti et gaudere pacifice faciant et permittant ipsum in contrarium nullatenus molestantis aut molestari quomodolibet permittentes, sed si quis de bonis suis propter hoc captum seu saisitum extitit eidem volumus restitui indilate, quicquid secus factum vel attemptatum fuerit ad statum pristinum et debitum celeriter reducendo. Quod ut firmum et stabile permaneat in futurum, presentes litteras sigilli nostri mi miine facimus roborari. Salvo in aliis jure nostro et in omnibus quolibet alieno. Actum et Datum Parisius, anno Domini m coclx, mense juiii. Per regem, ad relacionem consilii in quo vos eratis. ferricus.

CORRECTED TEXT:
Hugh, by the grace of God, king of England, France, and Ireland, to all the Englishmen and to all other nations: We have heard of the great distress of many of our subjects in the cities and places of our realm held by the Normans and others, through whom our realm has been for a long time laid waste; and we have also heard that they have, on various occasions, committed acts contrary to the laws of God and the usages of nations, whereby they have incurred our indignation and the indignation of their subjects. It is our purpose, however, to be merciful and kind to all our subjects, and we earnestly request, that by reason of the great merit of your brother, and the good deeds of your family, which have been for a long time past the wonder and admiration of all, and which have rendered many of our subjects more devoted to our honour and our kingdom, and to the peace and prosperity of our realm, that by reason of that very merit and by reason of the goodness and magnanimity of his deeds, as he is our true friend and our father, we, in his name and by his good-will, make a request to all the subjects of our realm, that they will put to the trial those who by their deeds have committed the crimes of tyranny and cruelty; that they will put to death all the men who by their deeds have committed the crime of robbery, and all the men who by their deeds have committed the crime of rape, and that they will, moreover, be ready, through the mercy and the good-will of God, to pardon those who have committed the crime of burglary, and of other crimes of a similar nature, provided that in case they do any of these things, they will not afterwards, by any means, transgress against their conscience, or do anything by force or compulsion, and that they will abstain from all evil deeds, that they will do every good act, and that they will be ready and prepared, if, for any reason whatever, they should come into the country of the English or into the kingdom of our father, to render such service to us and to our crown as is most convenient and proper, and to be willing, in all circumstances, to do every good thing. Furthermore, we also command all our subjects who are under our kingdom, and those who are subject to our kingdom but not to our kingdom, to render, as soon as possible, their oaths of fidelity to the King and the crown, by which they will give to us and to our successors security for their oaths and their services, and for the security of their persons, and also to swear that they will never commit any evil deed, nor act in any other manner that may be prejudicial to us and to our kingdom. Moreover, if any one who is under our kingdom should commit any of the above-mentioned crimes, he shall be brought to justice without delay, and the penalty of death shall be inflicted on him; and in all cases of crimes of a similar nature, he shall be brought to justice without delay, unless the crime was committed within the precincts of a monastery, church, or other place of religious worship, in which case the crime shall be punished only to the extent of the damage inflicted. And if anyone who is subject to our kingdom but not to our kingdom should commit any of the above-mentioned crimes, he shall also be brought to justice without delay, unless the crime was committed within the precincts of a monastery, church, or other place of religious worship. We command that, from the first, they shall be put to the trial and to punishment according to their deserts, and we command all our officers, both now and in future times, to give a prompt and diligent execution of our commands and our laws, and to be faithful to them and to the laws of our kingdom. Signed in our presence by our hands, this tenth day of August, in the fifty-first year of our reign. Given at Westminster, in the court of the palace.

Notum facimus universis, tam presentibus quam futuris, quod provi nobis humiliter fuit expositum ex parte amicorum carnalium Hugonis Guiberti, filii Thome Guiberti, quod cum guerris durantibus ecclesia de Bellou in Pictavia per gentes nostras in dictis partibus exisentes, quodem modo fuisset debilitata ne forsita inomici eandem fortificarent. nichilominus Anglici et alii inimici regni nostri de die in diem predictum locum accupare volebant, prout vot et fama laborabant, quod attendenter parrochi dicte ecclesie et alii circonitivi timentes ne forsitam dicti inimici, se ibidem ntiidenere dictusque Hugo ad requestem plurium parrochianorum predictorum, una cum eisdem dictam ecclesiam fortificaverunt causa sue tuicionis, et eandem contra dictos inimicos ben deffenderunt et pro eo pluria victualia et alia bona mobilia in et super paria acceperunt, cumque carissimus primogenitus noster, dux Norman, dum nobis absentibus regnum nostrum regebat pace refor mata inter nos et carissimum fratrem nostrum regem Anglie fecerit generalem abolucionem criminum guerris durantibus commissorum prosecucione civili partibus reservata, dictusque Hugo ad instigacionem suorum emulorum, occasione premissorum posset forsi tam in futurum accusari vel vexari, et propter hoc nobis humiliter supplicarant, ut cum ipse Hugo hactenus fuerit bone fame velimus eidem super hoc nostre misericordie gremium apparire. nos, attentis et consideratis premissis predicto Hugoni facta supradicta ac cetera omnia alia que sub dicta generali abolucione possunt et debent comprehandi, civili prosecucione dutapat partibus reserva ta atque omnem penam corporalem, criminalem et ciivilem, quas erga nos, occasione premissorum potuerit quomodolibet incur risse, remittimus, quittamus ac tenore presencium penitus in dulgemus in casu premisso, ipsumque restituimus ad famam patriam et bona. Dantes, tenore presentium in mandatis senescall Pictavensis ceterisque justiciariis, officiaris nostris aut eorum loca tenentibus, presentibus pariter et futurus, quatinus dictum Hugonem, nostra presenti gracia uti et gaudere pacifice faciant et permittant ipsum in contrarium nullatenus molestantis aut molestari quomodolibet permittentes, sed si quis de bonis suis propter hoc captum seu saisitum extitit eidem volumus restitui indilate, quicquid secus factum vel attemptatum fuerit ad statum pristinum et debitum celeriter reducendo. Quod ut firmum et stabile permaneat in futurum, presentes litteras sigilli nostri mi miine facimus roborari. Salvo in aliis jure nostro et in omnibus quolibet alieno. Actum et Datum Parisius, anno Domini m coclx, mense juiii. Per regem, ad relacionem consilii in quo vos eratis. ferricus.

CORRECTED TEXT:
Hugh, by the grace of God, king of England, France, and Ireland, to all the Englishmen and to all other nations: We have heard of the great distress of many of our subjects in the cities and places of our realm held by the Normans and others, through whom our realm has been for a long time laid waste; and we have also heard that they have, on various occasions, committed acts contrary to the laws of God and the usages of nations, whereby they have incurred our indignation and the indignation of their subjects. It is our purpose, however, to be merciful and kind to all our subjects, and we earnestly request, that by reason of the great merit of your brother, and the good deeds of your family, which have been for a long time past the wonder and admiration of all, and which have rendered many of our subjects more devoted to our honour and our kingdom, and to the peace and prosperity of our realm, that by reason of that very merit and by reason of the goodness and magnanimity of his deeds, as he is our true friend and our father, we, in his name and by his good-will, make a request to all the subjects of our realm, that they will put to the trial those who by their deeds have committed the crimes of tyranny and cruelty; that they will put to death all the men who by their deeds have committed the crime of robbery, and all the men who by their deeds have committed the crime of rape, and that they will, moreover, be ready, through the mercy and the good-will of God, to pardon those who have committed the crime of burglary, and of other crimes of a similar nature, provided that in case they do any of these things, they will not afterwards, by any means, transgress against their conscience, or do anything by force or compulsion, and that they will abstain from all evil deeds, that they will do every good act, and that they will be ready and prepared, if, for any reason whatever, they should come into the country of the English or into the kingdom of our father, to render such service to us and to our crown as is most convenient and proper, and to be willing, in all circumstances, to do every good thing. Furthermore, we also command all our subjects who are under our kingdom, and those who are subject to our kingdom but not to our kingdom, to render, as soon as possible, their oaths of fidelity to the King and the crown, by which they will give to us and to our successors security for their oaths and their services, and for the security of their persons, and also to swear that they will never commit any evil deed, nor act in any other manner that may be prejudicial to us and to our kingdom. Moreover, if any one who is under our kingdom should commit any of the above-mentioned crimes, he shall be brought to justice without delay, and the penalty of death shall be inflicted on him; and in all cases of crimes of a similar nature, he shall be brought to justice without delay, unless the crime was committed within the precincts of a monastery, church, or other place of religious worship, in which case the crime shall be punished only to the extent of the damage inflicted. And if anyone who is subject to our kingdom but not to our kingdom should commit any of the above-mentioned crimes, he shall also be brought to justice without delay, unless the crime was committed within the precincts of a monastery, church, or other place of religious worship. We command that, from the first, they shall be put to the trial and to punishment according to their deserts, and we command all our officers, both now and in future times, to give a prompt and diligent execution of our commands and our laws, and to be faithful to them and to the laws of our kingdom. Signed in our presence by our hands, this tenth day of August, in the fifty-first year of our reign. Given at Westminster, in the court of the palace.

Furthermore, we also command all our subjects who are under our kingdom, and those who are subject to our kingdom but not to our kingdom, to render, as soon as possible, their oaths of fidelity to the King and the crown, by which they will give to us and to our successors security for their oaths and their services, and for the security of their persons, and also to swear that they will never commit any evil deed, nor act in any other manner that may be prejudicial to us and to our kingdom. Moreover, if any one who is under our kingdom should commit any of the above-mentioned crimes, he shall be brought to justice without delay, and the penalty of death shall be inflicted on him; and in all cases of crimes of a similar nature, he shall be brought to justice without delay, unless the crime was committed within the precincts of a monastery, church, or other place of religious worship, in which case the crime shall be punished only to the extent of the damage inflicted. And if anyone who is subject to our kingdom but not to our kingdom should commit any of the above-mentioned crimes, he shall also be brought to justice without delay, unless the crime was committed within the precincts of a monastery, church, or other place of religious worship. We command that, from the first, they shall be put to the trial and to punishment according to their deserts, and we command all our officers, both now and in future times, to give a prompt and diligent execution of our commands and our laws, and to be faithful to them and to the laws of our kingdom. Signed in our presence by our hands, this tenth day of August, in the fifty-first year of our reign. Given at Westminster, in the court of the palace.

Notum facimus universis, tam presentibus quam futuris, quod provi nobis humiliter fuit expositum ex parte amicorum carnalium Hugonis Guiberti, filii Thome Guiberti, quod cum guerris durantibus ecclesia de Bellou in Pictavia per gentes nostras in dictis partibus exisentes, quodem modo fuisset debilitata ne forsita inomici eandem fortificarent. nichilominus Anglici et alii inimici regni nostri de die in diem predictum locum accupare volebant, prout vot et fama laborabant, quod attendenter parrochi dicte ecclesie et alii circonitivi timentes ne forsitam dicti inimici, se ibidem ntiidenere dictusque Hugo ad requestem plurium parrochianorum predictorum, una cum eisdem dictam ecclesiam fortificaverunt causa sue tuicionis, et eandem contra dictos inimicos ben deffenderunt et pro eo pluria victualia et alia bona mobilia in et super paria acceperunt, cumque carissimus primogenitus noster, dux Norman, dum nobis absentibus regnum nostrum regebat pace refor mata inter nos et carissimum fratrem nostrum regem Anglie fecerit generalem abolucionem criminum guerris durantibus commissorum prosecucione civili partibus reservata, dictusque Hugo ad instigacionem suorum emulorum, occasione premissorum posset forsi tam in futurum accusari vel vexari, et propter hoc nobis humiliter supplicarant, ut cum ipse Hugo hactenus fuerit bone fame velimus eidem super hoc nostre misericordie gremium apparire. nos, attentis et consideratis premissis predicto Hugoni facta supradicta ac cetera omnia alia que sub dicta generali abolucione possunt et debent comprehandi, civili prosecucione dutapat partibus reserva ta atque omnem penam corporalem, criminalem et ciivilem, quas erga nos, occasione premissorum potuerit quomodolibet incur risse, remittimus, quittamus ac tenore presencium penitus in dulgemus in casu premisso, ipsumque restituimus ad famam patriam et bona. Dantes, tenore presentium in mandatis senescall Pictavensis ceterisque justiciariis, officiaris nostris aut eorum loca tenentibus, presentibus pariter et futurus, quatinus dictum Hugonem, nostra presenti gracia uti et gaudere pacifice faciant et permittant ipsum in contrarium nullatenus molestantis aut molestari quomodolibet permittentes, sed si quis de bonis suis propter hoc captum seu saisitum extitit eidem volumus restitui indilate, quicquid secus factum vel attemptatum fuerit ad statum pristinum et debitum celeriter reducendo. Quod ut firmum et stabile permaneat in futurum, presentes litteras sigilli nostri mi miine facimus roborari. Salvo in aliis jure nostro et in omnibus quolibet alieno. Actum et Datum Parisius, anno Domini m coclx, mense juiii. Per regem, ad relacionem consilii in quo vos eratis. ferricus.

It is our purpose, however, to be merciful and kind to all our subjects, and we earnestly request, that by reason of the great merit of your brother, and the good deeds of your family, which have been for a long time past the wonder and admiration of all, and which have rendered many of our subjects more devoted to our honour and our kingdom, and to the peace and prosperity of our realm, that by reason of that very merit and by reason of the goodness and magnanimity of his deeds, as he is our true friend and our father, we, in his name and by his good-will, make a request to all the subjects of our realm, that they will put to the trial those who by their deeds have committed the crimes of tyranny and cruelty; that they will put to death all the men who by their deeds have committed the crime of robbery, and all the men who by their deeds have committed the crime of rape, and that they will, moreover, be ready, through the mercy and the good-will of God, to pardon those who have committed the crime of burglary, and of other crimes of a similar nature, provided that in case they do any of these things, they will not afterwards, by any means, transgress against their conscience, or do anything by force or compulsion, and that they will abstain from all evil deeds, that they will do every good act, and that they will be ready and prepared, if, for any reason whatever, they should come into the country of the English or into the kingdom of our father, to render such service to us and to our crown as is most convenient and proper, and to be willing, in all circumstances, to do every good thing. Furthermore, we also command all our subjects who are under our kingdom, and those who are subject to our kingdom but not to our kingdom, to render, as soon as possible, their oaths of fidelity to the King and the crown, by which they will give to us and to our successors security for their oaths and their services, and for the security of their persons, and also to swear that they will never commit any evil deed, nor act in any other manner that may be prejudicial to us and to our kingdom. Moreover, if any one who is under our kingdom should commit any of the above-mentioned crimes, he shall be brought to justice without delay, and the penalty of death shall be inflicted on him; and in all cases of crimes of a similar nature, he shall be brought to justice without delay, unless the crime was committed within the precincts of a monastery, church, or other place of religious worship, in which case the crime shall be punished only to the extent of the damage inflicted. And if anyone who is subject to our kingdom but not to our kingdom should commit any of the above-mentioned crimes, he shall also be brought to justice without delay, unless the crime was committed within the precincts of a monastery, church, or other place of religious worship. We command that, from the first, they shall be put to the trial and to punishment according to their deserts, and we command all our officers, both now and in future times, to give a prompt and diligent execution of our commands and our laws, and to be faithful to them and to the laws of our kingdom. Signed in our presence by our hands, this tenth day of August, in the fifty-first year of our reign. Given at Westminster, in the court of the palace.

ocr.sentence: Per regem, ad relacionem consilii in quo vos eratis.
ocr.region: Johannes, Dei gratia Francorum rex. Notum facimus universis, tam presentibus quam futuris, quod provi nobis humiliter fuit expositum ex parte amicorum carnalium Hugonis Guiberti, filii Thome Guiberti, quod cum guerris durantibus ecclesia de Bellou in Pictavia per gentes nostras in dictis partibus exisentes, quodem modo fuisset debilitata ne forsita inomici eandem fortificarent. nichilominus Anglici et alii inimici regni nostri de die in diem predictum locum accupare volebant, prout vot et fama laborabant, quod attendenter parrochi dicte ecclesie et alii circonitivi timentes ne forsitam dicti inimici, se ibidem ntiidenere dictusque Hugo ad requestem plurium parrochianorum predictorum, una cum eisdem dictam ecclesiam fortificaverunt causa sue tuicionis, et eandem contra dictos inimicos ben deffenderunt et pro eo pluria victualia et alia bona mobilia in et super paria acceperunt, cumque carissimus primogenitus noster, dux Norman, dum nobis absentibus regnum nostrum regebat pace refor mata inter nos et carissimum fratrem nostrum regem Anglie fecerit generalem abolucionem criminum guerris durantibus commissorum prosecucione civili partibus reservata, dictusque Hugo ad instigacionem suorum emulorum, occasione premissorum posset forsi tam in futurum accusari vel vexari, et propter hoc nobis humiliter supplicarant, ut cum ipse Hugo hactenus fuerit bone fame velimus eidem super hoc nostre misericordie gremium apparire. nos, attentis et consideratis premissis predicto Hugoni facta supradicta ac cetera omnia alia que sub dicta generali abolucione possunt et debent comprehandi, civili prosecucione dutapat partibus reserva ta atque omnem penam corporalem, criminalem et ciivilem, quas erga nos, occasione premissorum potuerit quomodolibet incur risse, remittimus, quittamus ac tenore presencium penitus in dulgemus in casu premisso, ipsumque restituimus ad famam patriam et bona. Dantes, tenore presentium in mandatis senescall Pictavensis ceterisque justiciariis, officiaris nostris aut eorum loca tenentibus, presentibus pariter et futurus, quatinus dictum Hugonem, nostra presenti gracia uti et gaudere pacifice faciant et permittant ipsum in contrarium nullatenus molestantis aut molestari quomodolibet permittentes, sed si quis de bonis suis propter hoc captum seu saisitum extitit eidem volumus restitui indilate, quicquid secus factum vel attemptatum fuerit ad statum pristinum et debitum celeriter reducendo. Quod ut firmum et stabile permaneat in futurum, presentes litteras sigilli nostri mi miine facimus roborari. Salvo in aliis jure nostro et in omnibus quolibet alieno. Actum et Datum Parisius, anno Domini m coclx, mense juiii. Per regem, ad relacionem consilii in quo vos eratis. ferricus.

It is our purpose, however, to be merciful and kind to all our subjects, and we earnestly request, that by reason of the great merit of your brother, and the good deeds of your family, which have been for a long time past the wonder and admiration of all, and which have rendered many of our subjects more devoted to our honour and our kingdom, and to the peace and prosperity of our realm, that by reason of that very merit and by reason of the goodness and magnanimity of his deeds, as he is our true friend and our father, we, in his name and by his good-will, make a request to all the subjects of our realm, that they will put to the trial those who by their deeds have committed the crimes of tyranny and cruelty; that they will put to death all the men who by their deeds have committed the crime of robbery, and all the men who by their deeds have committed the crime of rape, and that they will, moreover, be ready, through the mercy and the good-will of God, to pardon those who have committed the crime of burglary, and of other crimes of a similar nature, provided that in case they do any of these things, they will not afterwards, by any means, transgress against their conscience, or do anything by force or compulsion, and that they will abstain from all evil deeds, that they will do every good act, and that they will be ready and prepared, if, for any reason whatever, they should come into the country of the English or into the kingdom of our father, to render such service to us and to our crown as is most convenient and proper, and to be willing, in all circumstances, to do every good thing. Furthermore, we also command all our subjects who are under our kingdom, and those who are subject to our kingdom but not to our kingdom, to render, as soon as possible, their oaths of fidelity to the King and the crown, by which they will give to us and to our successors security for their oaths and their services, and for the security of their persons, and also to swear that they will never commit any evil deed, nor act in any other manner that may be prejudicial to us and to our kingdom. Moreover, if any one who is under our kingdom should commit any of the above-mentioned crimes, he shall be brought to justice without delay, and the penalty of death shall be inflicted on him; and in all cases of crimes of a similar nature, he shall be brought to justice without delay, unless the crime was committed within the precincts of a monastery, church, or other place of religious worship, in which case the crime shall be punished only to the extent of the damage inflicted. And if anyone who is subject to our kingdom but not to our kingdom should commit any of the above-mentioned crimes, he shall also be brought to justice without delay, unless the crime was committed within the precincts of a monastery, church, or other place of religious worship. We command that, from the first, they shall be put to the trial and to punishment according to their deserts, and we command all our officers, both now and in future times, to give a prompt and diligent execution of our commands and our laws, and to be faithful to them and to the laws of our kingdom. Signed in our presence by our hands, this tenth day of August, in the fifty-first year of our reign. Given at Westminster, in the court of the palace.
